data.name: Octant
data.description: Octant is a platform that enables users to lock GLM, earn ETH rewards, and fund projects they care about.

Open Source (OS) Observer is an analytics platform that makes it easy to discover, monitor, and support valuable open source software. You can think of it like “Dune Analytics for Digital Public Goods”.

We have already started indexing on-chain and off-chain data about open source funders, organizations, contributors, and users. 

Next, we want to build an API for users to retrieve metrics about projects’ work and financial activities. Users will be able to easily take these metrics and issue their own distinct, quantitative impact evaluations (think: Lists ✨ for RPGF3). Metrics include areas like market share (level of decentralization), nature of contract interactions, user attribution and activity, forward and reverse dependencies, team size and momentum, and financial flows.

Eventually, we want to build a robust frontend for users to create and share their own impact dashboards.

The project aims to launch an Arbitrum OSS directory with auto-validation and reward mechanisms for community submissions, expand the directory to feature at least 200 prominent projects on Arbitrum across different domains with comprehensive data from both on-chain and off-chain sources, and utilize this data to propose an initial set of 4-5 ""impact pools"" that gauge projects' contributions to ecosystem health metrics such as new user growth, developer activity, and sequencer fees.

questions.query: How should the success of your grant be measured?
questions.explanation:
This specific grant should be measured based on (a) whether all milestones are met, and (b) the degree to which a critical number of established OSS projects in the Arbitrum ecosystem are represented on Open Source Observer.

Beyond these objectives, the grant will have been a success if OSO's proposed impact pools and other quantitative insights about ecosystem health inform the DAO’s grantmaking future decisions.

questions.query: What is the intended direct impact your project will have on the ecosystem?
questions.explanation:
We believe the Arbitrum DAO, as a large and highly decentralized community, has a critical need for the infrastructure OSO provides, enabling scalable, cost-efficient grantmaking and permissionless impact evaluation.

We provide a strong incentive for projects to open source their full code base. This, in turn, enables us and our users to observe teams’ progress and index the artifacts of their work. Moreover, by making the impact data required by the community highly visible, we make it easier for DAO governance to iterate and align funding against impact outcomes.

Unlike tools that focus solely on onchain data, OSO recognizes the contributions of developer libraries and other upstream code contributions that enable more dapps to deploy on Arbitrum. We also provide baseline data to measure Arbitrum teams against other ecosystems or types of projects.

questions.query: What is the long-term impact of your grant?
questions.explanation: In the long-term, we hope that OSO can enable a higher "impact ROI" per unit of ARB invested in the ecosystem. We will offer the data to establish counterfactuals and measure grant performance over time. If the community decides to fly blind and ignore the data, then it will have no impact. If the community decides to leverage the data, then it can have significant impact, ideally improving impact ROI by at least 20% along the prioritized impact pools.

questions.query: How will the grant funds be used?
questions.explanation: The grant funds will be used to support the full-time team working on OSO (two engineers, one data/community lead), to fund community data bounties, and to cover data infrastructure costs.

questions.query: What is the timeframe for the work funded?
questions.explanation: Around 3 months. The project began in late November / early December and is expected to wrap-up at the end of February.

questions.query: How will receiving a grant enable you to foster growth or innovation within the ecosystem?
questions.explanation: The grant will enable us to create an initial project registry and set of OSS metrics that the community can build on top of. Specifically, we want to engage the community to create impact metrics and evaluate grant effectiveness. We believe that better visibility on project metrics will lead to greater growth and innovation within the ecosystem, as stronger projects will get recognition and hopefully increased funding.

data.description:
Details: 

This phase represents the culmination of all the work done to bring Arbitrum onto OSO and the starting point for future grantmaking initiatives that can be powered by OSO’s impact metrics. We will engage the community and propose an initial set of impact pools. Each impact pool will target a different area of Arbitrum’s ecosystem health with its own specific input metrics. For example, a “Sustainable User Growth” pool might rate projects based on the number of high-value users they currently have, the number of retained users over a period of time, and the number of active users who are also active on other apps within the Arbitrum ecosystem. The pool itself would represent a portfolio of projects weighted by the degree to which they’ve contributed to this impact outcome. In the long run, OSO aims to pave the way for independent analysts and researchers to generate their own metrics and impact pools, so the initial 4-5 that we develop via this milestone will serve as a starting point and source of inspiration for the community. 

Deliverable: 

We curate 4-5 “impact pools” with transparent allocations and input metrics, covering more than 200 projects and various impact domains.

data.text:
Cross-posting ![image](https://forum.arbitrum.foundation/t/open-source-observer-x-arbitrum/20266/2) from the Arbitrum forum.

We recently completed our 2nd of 3 milestones:

> *2. Grow the directory to include at least 200 well-known projects building on Arbitrum across various domains (eg, DeFi, gaming, developer tooling, governance tooling, etc) with up-to-date, fully indexed data from on- and off-chain sources*

To mark the occasion, we released our first analysis on the state of OSS on Arbitrum, which you can find [here](https://docs.opensource.observer/blog/arb-ecosystem-analysis) and in [this post on X](https://x.com/OSObserver/status/1752882450319974568?s=20). It covers a total of 345 projects building on Arbitrum. You can help us add / update information for projects by [making a PR here](https://github.com/opensource-observer/oss-directory).

Some highlights:

1. We are currently tracking over 300 OSS projects and over 13,000 code artifacts that are making an impact on the Arbitrum ecosystem. These artifacts include both GitHub repos (~10,000) and smart contracts deployed on Arbitrum One (~3,000).
2. Approximately 1,800 developers are actively engaged in these projects. This number aligns closely with the latest [Electric Capital Developer Report](https://www.developerreport.com/ecosystems/arbitrum). Our analysis, however, incorporates an additional 94 projects not currently captured in their registry.
3. The number of active developers is 18% lower than the peak of around 2,200 in March 2023. It's important to note, however, that this reduction is primarily concentrated in a few projects rather than a general decline across the ecosystem. In fact, the majority of projects have maintained a stable developer count over the past year.

![image|690x329](https://docs.opensource.observer/assets/images/area-arbitrum-all-aed9f7bf689bd55482aebafe088c9aea.png)

This was just a small taste of what's possible with the data we’re collecting. In early February, we will release a follow-up report that covers the onchain contributions of ~200 of the 300+ projects included here. At the end of February, we will leverage the data to propose an initial 4-5 “impact pools” that can inform future grantmaking efforts by Plurality Labs and the Arbitrum DAO.

You can explore the Python notebook and some static data dumps [here](https://github.com/opensource-observer/insights/). And again, check out the full report [here](https://docs.opensource.observer/blog/arb-ecosystem-analysis).

data.name: Arbitrum
data.description: EVM L2 network

The goal of Open Source Observer is to measure the ROI of funding open source teams.

Specifically, we help open source communities and funders:

- Track the full downstream impact of grants programs on key ecosystem metrics like user growth and developer activity over time
- Create reward functions that allocate funding to projects based on impact analysis
- Deep dive well-known projects and minimize bias

We’re putting all the metrics needed to inform better decision-making and grantmaking in one place, including:

- Impact: trace a project’s downstream contribution to end users, revenue, ecosystem growth, and sustainability by linking it to platform metrics
- Activity: graph a project’s team, momentum, and dependencies from GitHub and package managers
- Financing: estimate funding and burn rates from grant metadata and analysis of public financial reports

We are building Open Source Observer entirely as a public good, not just with open source and open data, but with truly open infrastructure. We want to make the data and analyses as widely available as possible and are committed to sharing our infrastructure directly with the community.

data.title: Epoch 5 updates

data.text:
### **Milestones and Deliverables**

- **Milestone 1**:
    - **Description**: Coverage growth.
    - **Immediate Outcome**: We have continued to expand our coverage of projects, repos, and contracts in the Etheruem ecosystem. As of July, our coverage included: 2,385 projects (+10% from June), 46K open source repos (+23% from June), and 127M smart contracts. The smart contract figure includes “discovered contracts” downstream from project deployers or factory contracts. In June, there were 10,619 active contributors across these projects — up from 10,396 in May.
    - **Funding Used**: na (however, this was approximately 15% level of effort for the team)
- **Milestone 2**:
    - **Description**: Launch of data exchange.
    - **Immediate Outcome**: We launched the [OSO Data Exchange](https://www.opensource.observer/data), a free public data exchange that in includes every model in the OSO pipeline, raw blocks/transactions/traces across 7 chains in the OP Superchain (OP Mainnet, Base, Frax, Metal, Mode, PGN, Zora), GitHub repo and developer activity, Gitcoin Grants and Passport, OpenRank, Farcaster, and Lens datasets. In the first month, more than 5 developer teams signed up for access and consumed a combined 90 TB of data.
    - **Funding Used**: na (however, this was approximately 50% level of effort for the team)
- **Milestone 3**:
    - **Description**: Protocol metrics v1.
    - **Immediate Outcome**: We powered Optimism’s latest Retro Funding round with protocol-level impact metrics. OSO worked with Optimism’s Citizen House to develop 16 onchain impact metrics and apply them consistently across 230 projects and 6 OP stack chains. Read all about it [here](https://docs.opensource.observer/blog/impact-metrics-rf4-deep-dive). This work directly informed the allocation of 10M OP.
    - **Funding Used**: na (however, this was approximately 35% level of effort for the team)
- **Karma GAP**: https://gap.karmahq.xyz/project/open-source-observer

"""
### **Challenges**

- **Previous Challenges**:
    - **Description**: In the last submission, we highlighted the challenge of scaling our data processing infrastructure to handle the increasing volume of data from various sources. We tripled our data volume since the last epoch, and now have more than 200 models running on top of it. This put a huge strain on our existing infrastructure, leading to performance bottlenecks and slower query times.
    - **Updates**: We have made significant progress by deploying a new GraphQL API service built on a scalable Clickhouse cluster, which has notably improved query performance.
    - **Resolution**: The resolution involved a lot of backend work to upgrade our infrastructure, specifically by swapping out CloudSQL with Clickhouse, and wiring up the new GraphQL API endpoint. We also enhanced our documentation for developer teams to better understand how to interact with the new API service.
    - **Lessons Learned**: One of the key lessons learned is how rapidly data processing costs can escalate as data volumes grow. We are now more mindful of the need to continuously optimize our infrastructure to ensure efficient data processing and delivery.

### **Outputs and Outcomes**

**Outputs (Last Epoch)**:

- **Output 1**: Launched the OSO Data Exchange, offering a free public data exchange that includes models and datasets from 7 chains within the OP Superchain.
- **Output 2**: Powered Optimism's Retro Funding round with 16 on-chain impact metrics, applied across 230 projects and 6 OP stack chains.

**Short-term Outcomes**:

- **Outcome 1**: Increased community engagement, particularly among developers integrating our data into their projects, as evidenced by new integrations like Pairwise, Retrolist, and RetroPGF Hub.
- **Outcome 2**: Observed high demand for the OSO Data Exchange, with over 5 developer teams signing up for access and consuming a significant amount of data (90TB) within the first month.

**Long-term Outcomes**:

- **Outcome 1**: Helped Optimism allocate 10M OP based on the impact metrics provided by OSO, demonstrating the potential of comparable impact metrics for other funders in the ecosystem.
- **Outcome 2**: Increased coverage to 2,385 projects, 46K open-source repos, and 127M smart contracts, providing the most comprehensive, fully open source / open infra view of the Ethereum ecosystem for developers and data scientists.

    **Metrics for Outcomes:**
    
    1. **Funding Allocation**: 10M OP allocated by Optimism based on OSO's impact metrics.
    2. **Data Utilization**: 90TB of data consumed by developer teams within the first month of launching the OSO Data Exchange.
    3. **Coverage Expansion**: 10% increase in projects, 23% increase in open-source repos, and 127M smart contracts covered by OSO.
    4. **Project Integrations**: total of 9 teams currently integrating OSO data into their projects (five via the OSO Data Exchange and four via direct API access).


### **Plans for Potential Funds Raised in the Next Octant Allocation Window**

- **Goal 1**:
    - **Description**: Expand the OSO Data Exchange to include additional data sources (eg, software dependencies) and integrations with other L2s.
    - **Expected Outcome**: Increased adoption of the OSO Data Exchange across multiple ecosystems, leading to greater coverage, more ecosystem-specific insights, and more integrations with developer partners.
    - **Funding Needed**: approx $10K per month per chain for indexing and storage costs, plus metrics for ~200 projects per chain.
- **Goal 2**:
    - **Description**: Develop advanced analytics and visualization tools to better showcase the insights derived from OSO data.
    - **Expected Outcome**: Reboot of the OSO website to include timeseries datasets, artifact-level page views, and dynamic ecosystem reporting (eg, live stats for all Octant Projects).
    - **Funding Needed**: $50,000 (this will be the focus of our Epoch 4 funding)

### **Other Funding**

- **Grant Funding Received Since the Last Epoch**: We have not received any new liquid grants since the last epoch.
- **Other Non-Grant Funding Sources**: n/a

### **Future Plans for Financial Sustainability**

We are lean, and our primary costs are infrastructure and developer salaries. We are exploring recurring revenue streams and backstopping grants with some of our L2 partners. Octant funding makes a huge difference in our ability to continue to grow and scale our impact!

Cross-posted from: https://discuss.octant.app/t/open-source-observer-measure-the-impact-of-open-source-contributions/119/7

* Our coverage currently includes 3,063 projects, 82K open source repos, and 142M smart contracts. We added 600 new projects and nearly 40K new repos since August.
* We’ve integrated [Open Source Insights](http://deps.dev/) data to build dependency-related models, analyzing when packages become or cease to be dependencies.
* We enhanced [OSS Funding](https://github.com/opensource-observer/oss-funding), our curated registry of grants and funding for open source projects, with a standardized schema that maps funders and grant rounds to projects.
* We prototyped a pilot for [AutoRetroFunding](https://retrofunding.vercel.app/) at ETHGlobal SF, a platform for continuous retroactive funding allocation. The platform earned hackathon prizes from Polygon, Uniswap, and Nouns DAO.
* We launched a design refresh on our [website](https://www.opensource.observer/), along with dedicated product pages ([API](https://www.opensource.observer/product/api), dashboard [terminal](https://www.opensource.observer/product/terminal), data [warehouse](https://www.opensource.observer/product/warehouse)), and use case pages (grant [analytics](https://www.opensource.observer/use-cases/grants), [network graphs](https://www.opensource.observer/use-cases/graphs), [retro funding](https://www.opensource.observer/use-cases/retrofunding)).

For more product features and community engagement updates, check out our latest newsletter [here](https://kariba.substack.com/p/kariba-update-november-2024).
